IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
Driver: Justin Alan Shockley (W/M 10/01/1990)                
MD ID: MD10272881045
DUI #: 23-96-062
Video: V30 MVR Operational (VIDEO LABELED 23MSP009896) BWC Operational

Narrative:
On 03/19/2023, at approximately 0135 hours, I, Tpr Jenkins #7357 was operating a stationary RADAR assignment E/B Rt 50 at the Harry Kelley Bridge.

Vehicle in Motion:
At that time, I witnessed a lifted up, gray Ram pickup traveling W/B in lane one across the Harry Kelley bridge, at what appeared to be above the posted speed limit of 35 miles per hour. I activated my Kustom Golden Eagle II RADAR front antennae and observed a speed of 49 miles per hour. The vehicle was the only one in the RADAR beam at that time. While the vehicle appeared to have its front “running lights” operational, the rear of the vehicle did not have any lights on and was completely dark. I then proceeded to turn around in order to conduct a traffic stop on the vehicle. As I continued to observe the vehicle traveling W/B, it swerved from side to side in its lane and upon turning right onto Golf Course Rd, it crossing the double yellow line by approximately half the width of the vehicle into the opposing traffic lane. The vehicle then sped up to approximately 60 MPH in a posted 30 MPH zone. I then activated my emergency equipment in order to conduct a traffic stop on the vehicle. The vehicle then sharply turned left into the driveway of the operator’s residence at 10106 Golf Course Rd. The vehicle was later identified as a 2019 Ram 2500 bearing Maryland registration 7EG8539 and was registered to the operator of the vehicle. I am certified by the Maryland State Police to operate RADAR, it was tested before and after my tour of duty and was found to be working properly.

Personal Contact:
Upon contact with the driver who I later identified as Justin Alan Shockley (W/M 10/01/1990), I detected a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from his breath and person. Shockley’s  speech was slurred and lethargic. Shockley would mumble and slur his words while speaking. I could detect a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from his breath and person. Shockley advised he did not have his license in his possession and displayed a United States issued passport. It was later discovered Shockley’s Maryland issued driver’s license was previously confiscation from a DUI he had received in February of 2023. Shockley was wearing a purple wristband from Pickle’s Pub on his right wrist.

Pre-Arrest Screening:
Shockley was asked where he was coming from that evening, he replied “Pickle’s”. When asked how much he had to drink that evening, Shockley advised he had two beers at M.R. Ducks. When asked about the purple wristband on his right wrist, Shockley replied “I have no wristbands”. I then pointed out that he was wearing a wristband from Pickle’s Pub, prompting him to acknowledge it was from earlier in the evening. Shockley advised he did not have any issues with his eyes and that he did not wear glasses. Shockley advised he did not take any prescriptions or medications. While speaking with Shockley, his speech was slurred and discombobulated. I could still detect a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from his breath and person while speaking with Shockley.

HGN: (6/6)
Prior to conducting this test, I deactivated my emergency equipment and positioned Shockley in a manner that was away from passing traffic or lights to minimize distraction. I explained the test to Shockley, I explained that he would be following my pen with his eyes and eyes only. I reminded him to keep his head straight, not move it from side to side. He advised that he understood my instructions and did not have any questions. I held my pen twelve (12) to fifteen (15) inches from Shockley’s nose, slightly above eye level. Shockley acknowledged he could see the tip of the pen. I told him to focus on the tip of the pen, to which he acknowledged. I observed equal tracking and equal pupil size. Shockley’s eyes were extremely glassy. Shockley displayed the following:

- Lack of smooth pursuit in both eyes
-Distinct and Sustained Nystagmus at Maximum Deviation in both eyes
- Onset of Nystagmus prior to 45 degrees in both eyes

Shockley had to be reminded to follow the tip of the pen several times as he would stop looking at the pen and instead look straight ahead. Shockley advised the light from my flashlight was “blinding” to him, I informed him I had the light shining on his stomach and not in his face.

Walk and Turn (WAT): (5/8)
Shockley was asked if he had any issues walking, he replied that he did not and that he felt comfortable performing the test in the shoes he was wearing. Shockley was instructed to imagine a straight line in front of him. Shockley asked if I wanted him to “walk downhill” claiming his driveway was on a hill. Shockley was advised that the part of his driveway we were using was flat and free from debris. Shockley was asked if he normally had issued walking on his driveway when he was sober, to which he replied, “I don’t know”. Shockley was placed into the instructional position with his left foot on the line, his right foot in front of his left touching heel-toe, and his arms down at his sides. Shockley was instructed to remain in this position while I explained the test to him.
 Shockley was instructed he would be taking nine hell-toe steps, looking down at his feet, and counting his steps aloud. On his ninth step, he was to leave his lead foot planted and take a series of small steps around it, then take nine heel-toe steps back to where he began. He was informed that once he started the test, he was not to stop until finished.
While in the instructional phase of the test, Shockley would fall off balance, put his left arm straight out to his side and lean on his nearby truck six times. Shockley was reminded multiple times not to lean on his truck.
Shockley left the instructional position and had to be placed back in it. Shockley started the test too soon before being told to do so.
During the first series of steps, Shockley missed hell-toe on step 6, 7, 8, and 9. Shockley stepped off line on steps 6 and 9.
After the first series of steps, Shockley performed an improper turn by picking up both of his feet, not conducting this portion of the test as instructed.
During the second series of steps, Shockley missed heel-toe on steps 1, 3, 7, 8, and 9. Shockley stepped off line on steps 2 and 6.
Shockley appeared to stagger his way through the test.

One Leg Stand Test (OLS): 2/4
Shockley was asked to submit to the One Leg Stand Test. Shockley was instructed to raise one of his feet of his choosing, approximately six inches off the ground. He was to keep his leg straight, look down at his raised foot, and count by thousandths until told to stop. Shockley advised he understood the instructions. Shockley chose to raise his right foot. Shockley attempted to begin the test before being told to do so.

During the first portion of the test (1-10 seconds)
Raised arms greater than six inches. Put foot down one time.
During the second portion of the test (11-20 seconds)
Raised arms greater than six inches. Put foot down two times.
During the final portion of the test (21-30 seconds)
Raised arms greater than six inches. Put foot down one time and remained down for last 7 seconds.


Preliminary Breath Test (PBT): Refused at approximately 0151 hours
The PBT was explained to Shockley who Refused to submit to the test at approximately 0151 hours.

Arrest:
Based on the above information and observations, I placed Shockley under arrest for driving while under the influence of alcohol at 0152 hours. Shockley was searched and placed in the front passenger seat of my vehicle. After being placed under arrest, His mouth was checked and found to be free of foreign material. During transport, I could still detect a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from his breath and person. Shockley would ramble on the ride back to the barrack and ask several times if I had grabbed his phone after he had already chosen to leave it at his home.

Intoximter: Refused approximately 0205 hours
After being read his DR-015 Advice of Rights, Shockley refused to submit to the Intoximeter test on at approximately 0205  hours. Shockley was processed and issued the appropriate paperwork. Shockley was released to his mother Doris Shockley at approximately 0254 hours.

Case closed by arrest.
All events occurred in Worcester County, Maryland.
